==American League== [[File:Nap Lajoie 1913.jpg|thumb|right|Nap Lajoie led the American League in its inaugural season with a .426 batting average, one of just 13 seasons of a .400+ average in the 20th century. In addition, Lajoie was a part of two separate contested batting average races in 1902 and 1910.|alt=A man with dark hair in a dark baseball cap and a white baseball jersey with "CLEVELAND" on the chest.]] [[File:Boggs.JPG|thumb|right|Wade Boggs won four consecutive batting titles from 1985 to 1988.|alt=Wade Boggs wearing the 2008 American League All-Star uniform]] [[File:George Brett - USS Reagan - Feb 2009.jpg|thumb|right|George Brett's .390 batting average in 1980 is the second-highest since 1941, the last season in which a player hit .400.|alt=An older man with short gray hair in a black and white horizontally striped shirt looks to his left.]] [[File:AAAA8040 Joe Mauer.jpg|thumb|right|Joe Mauer won the 2006, 2008, and 2009 batting titles, becoming the first catcher to win three batting titles and the only catcher to ever win in the AL.|alt=A man in a left-handed batting stance wearing pinstriped gray pants, a black shinguard on his right leg, a dark blue baseball jersey, and a dark-colored batting helmet.]] {| class="wikitable sortable" width="50%" |- !width="6%" halign="center"| Year !width="12%"| Winner !width="7%"| AVG !width="12%"| Team(s) !width="12%"| Runner-up !width="7%"| 2nd AVG !class="unsortable" width="2%"| Ref |- |[[1901 Major League Baseball season|1901]] |{{sortname|Nap|Lajoie}}<sup>â </sup> |.426 |[[Oakland Athletics|Philadelphia Athletics]] |{{sortname|Mike|Donlin}} |.340 |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1901-batting-leaders.shtml|title=1901 American League Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=April 19, 2010}}</ref> |- |[[1902 Major League Baseball season|1902]] |colspan=5 align="center"|'''Disputed'''{{ref label|laj|1902b|1902b}} |â |- |[[1903 Major League B