==Footnotes== *{{note label|League|L|L}}Recognized "major leagues" include the current [[American League|American]] and [[National League]]s and several defunct leagues â the [[American Association (19th century)|American Association]], the [[Federal League]], the [[Players' League]], and the [[Union Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/|title=Complete Baseball Team and Baseball Team Encyclopedias|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref> *{{note label|laj|1902a|1902a}}{{note label|laj|1902b|1902b}}Sources differ as to whether Nap Lajoie or Ed Delahanty won the American League batting title in 1902 and differ slightly over Lajoie's precise statistics that season. The [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Fame]] credits Lajoie with 129 hits in 352 at bats (.368)<ref name="lajhall">{{cite web|url=http://baseballhall.org/node/1241|title=Lajoie, Nap|work=baseballhall.org|publisher=Baseball Hall of Fame|accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref> while MLB and [[Baseball-Reference]] show 133 hits in 352 at bats (.378).<ref name="lajbref">{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/l/lajoina01.shtml|title=Nap Lajoie Statistics and History|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player.jsp?player_id=117414|title=Nap Lajoie Stats, Bio, Photos, Highlights|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref> According to Baseball-Reference a player qualified for a batting title prior to 1920 by appearing in 60% of their team's games&mdash;82 games in the 136 game schedule in 1902&mdash;and Lajoie appeared in 87 team games.<ref name="lajbref"/><ref name="faq">{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/about/faq.shtml|title=Frequently Asked Questions|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1902.shtml|title=1902 American League Season Summary|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref> As such, Baseball-Reference credits Lajoie with the 1902 title, with Delahanty's .376 batting average placing second.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1902-batting-leaders.shtml|title=1902 American League Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=April 19, 2010}}</ref> MLB's historical statistics leaderboards, however, use the modern standard of 3.1 plate appearances per team game (422 in that season) which Lajoie fell 37 short of.<ref name="lajbref"/> Thus, MLB credits Delahanty with the 1902 title with his .376 average.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/stats/historical/leaders.jsp?c_id=mlb&baseballScope=AL&statType=1&sortByStat=AVG&timeSubFrame2=1&timeFrame=1&timeSubFrame=1902|title=Historical Leaders|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=[[Major League Baseball]]|accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref> Similarly the Hall of Fame lists the 1902 title on Delahanty's plaque and not Lajoie's.<ref name="lajhall"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://baseballhall.org/hof/delahanty-ed|title=Delahanty, Ed|work=baseballhall.org|publisher=Baseball Hall of Fame|accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref> *{{note label|cobb|1910a|1910a}}{{note label|cobb|1910b|1910b}}Before the [[1910 Major League Baseball season|1910 season]], Hugh Chalmers of [[Chalmers Automobile]] announced he would present a Chalmers Model 30 automobile to the player with the highest batting average at the end of the season. The 1910 race for best average in the American League was between Nap Lajoie of the [[Cleveland Indians]] and the [[Detroit Tigers]]' widely disliked<ref name="ESPN">{{cite book|last=Gillette|first=Gary|coauthors=Palmer, Pete|title=The ESPN Baseball Encyclopedia|publisher=Sterling Publishing Co|location=New York City, New York|year=2007|edition=Fourth|pages=1764â1765|isbn=978-1-4027-4771-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mirrors of Sport|last=Doyle|first=Havey|date=July 4, 1941|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|page=18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/sportscentury/features/00014142.html|title=He was a pain ... but a great pain|last=Schwartz|first=Larry|work=[[ESPN.com]]|accessdate=January 19, 2010}}</ref> Cobb. On the last day of the season, Lajoie overtook Cobb's batting average with seven [[Bunt (baseball)|bunt]] hits in a [[Doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]] against the [[Baltimore Orioles|St. Louis Browns]]. Browns' [[Manager (baseball)|manager]] [[Jack O'Connor]] supposedly told his third baseman [[Red Corriden]] to [[Glossary of baseball (P)#playing back|play back down the line]] all day, which allowed Lajoie easy bunt hits.<ref name="browns">{{cite book|last=Vail|first=James|title=The road to Cooperstown: A critical history of baseball's Hall of Fame|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Yshg3i6KhfcC&lpg=PA209&ots=C-GKVF9Bgk&dq=%22nap%20lajoie%22%20%22seven%20bunt%20hits%22&pg=PA209#v=onepage&q=%22nap%20lajoie%22%20%22seven%20bunt%20hits%22&f=false|year=2001|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc.|page=209}}</ref> Cobb complained about the move, though American League President [[Ban Johnson]] said that a recalculation showed that Cobb had won the race anyway and Chalmers ultimately awarded cars to both players.<ref name="ESPN" /><ref name="browns"/> *{{note label|54ted|1954|1954}}Rules in 1954 required 2.6 at bats per team game, 400 for a 154-game schedule, to qualify for the title and hitless at bats could be added to reach this total.<ref name="faq"/> Ted Williams posted a .345 average in 1954 over only 386 at bats, and the required hitless at bats drop him below Avila's league-leading .341 average.<ref name="1954al"/>
